ernon] ''The Placenames Database of Ireland'' Retrieved 24 May 2015</ref> is a [[Barony (Ireland)|barony]] in the centre of [[County Westmeath]], in the [[Republic of Ireland]], formed by 1672.<ref name=\"Moyashel\">{{cite web|url=http://www.townlands.ie/westmeath/moyashel-and-maheradermon/|title=Moyashel and Maheradermon|website=townlands.ie|accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref> It is bordered by eight other baronies: [[Corkaree]] and [[Barony of Fore (County Westmeath)|Fore]] (to the north), [[Delvin (barony)|Delvin]] and [[Farbill]] (to the east), [[Fartullagh]] and [[Moycashel]] (to the south) and [[Rathconrath (barony)|Rathconrath]] and [[Moygoish]] (to the west). (Note that the town of [[Delvin]] and the village of [[Rathconrath]] are not synonymous with the baronies of the same name).\n\n==Geography==\nMoyashel and Magheradernon has an area of {{convert|43779.6|acre|km2}}.<ref name=\"Moyashel\" /> The barony contains parts of two large lakes; [[Lough Ennell]], shared with the barony of [[Fartullagh]], and [[Lough Owel]], an internationally recognised [[Ramsar convention|Ramsar]] waterfowl habitat. The [[River Brosna]], rises in Lough Owel<ref>[http://www.askaboutireland.ie/learning-zone/secondary-students/geography/regional-geography/lakelands-of-westmeath/lough-owel/index.xml Lough Owel] ''askaboutireland.ie'' Retrieved 24 May 2015</ref> and is a tributary of the [[River Shannon]]. The [[N4 road (Ireland)|N4]], a [[national primary road]] passes though the barony to the north of [[Mullingar]], connecting [[Dublin]] with the northwest of Ireland and the coastal town of [[Sligo]]. Railway lines carrying the national rail company [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]]'s [[Dublin]] to [[Longford]] commuter service and [[Dublin Connolly railway station|Dublin]] to [[Sligo]] intercity service<ref>[http://www.irishrail.ie/index.jsp?p=119&n=147 Irish Rail Printable Timetables] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402042758/http://www.irishrail.ie/train-timetables/timetables-by-route |date=2 April 2019 }} ''irishrail.ie'' Retrieved 24 May 2015</ref> stop in the barony at [[Mullingar railway station]]. The [[Royal Canal of Ireland|Royal Canal]] passes through the town of Mullingar connecting the [[River Liffey]] in Dublin to [[Longford Town, Longford|Longford town]].\n\n==Civil parishes of the barony ==\nThis table<ref>[http://www.logainm.ie/en/s?txt=in:266&cat=PAR Civil parishes of the barony of Moyashel and Magheradernon.] ''The Placenames Database of Ireland'' Retrieved 8 Jun 2015</ref> lists an historical geographical sub-division of the barony known as the [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]] (not to be confused with an [[Ecclesiastical parish]]).\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Name in English\n!Name in Irish\n|-\n|[[Dysart (civil parish)|Dysart]]\n|''An D\u00edseart''\n|-\n|[[Mullingar (civil parish)|Mullingar]]\n|''An Muileann gCearr''\n|-\n|[[Rathconnell (civil parish)|Rathconnell]]\n|''R\u00fa Chonaill''\n|}\n\n==Towns, villages and townlands==\n*[[Ballina, County Westmeath|Ballina]], a small village on the R390. Ballinea Bridge crosses over the Royal Canal. \n*[[Mullingar]] ({{Irish place name|An Muileann gCearr|the left-handed mill}}) is the [[county town]] of [[County Westmeath]].\n\nThere are 100 townlands in the barony of Moyashel and Magheradernon.<ref name=\"Moyashel\" />\n\n==Buildings of Interest==\n[[File:Sunset at Christ The King Cathedral.JPG|thumb|right|300px|Christ The King Cathedral at sunset]]\n*[[Cathedral of Christ the King, Mullingar|Christ The King Cathedral]], Mullingar\n{{clear}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/4238587 Map of Moyashel and Magheradernon] at openstreetmap.org\n*[http://www.townlands.ie/westmeath/moyashel-and-maheradermon/ Barony of Moyashel and Magheradernon, Co. Westmeath] at townlands.ie\n\n{{Portal|Ireland}}\n{{County Westmeath}}\n[[Category:Baronies of County Westmeath]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comme